I miss you like the dickens! In spite of a mad wish? that unclear me breathless. I feel lonely with you two gone. Eleanor's letter came this morning and I read it eagerly. And there you are just a couple of unclear hours away and it seems as if you were leagues away.

Two weeks ahead of time! He had a very rapid recovery. They thought it would be four weeks. And it was practically healed in two weeks. I am going over at one o'clock to bring him home.
He smoked his first cigar today. One of yours Sherwood.
He was very pleased with those cigars.
Everything comes at once. I should be here this next week or two to do the running? for Alice and Eddie. But there is the wedding. It can't be put off. Anna will probably go over and help Alice for a four weeks when I

Just here I was interrupted by the telephone. It was a call for you from Jack Troxell. He wanted to have you for dinner. Had been dying? to have an evening with the two of you. He asked when you would be back etc. I told him that I would see you soon and asked if there was a message and he gave me the above. "Very sorry to miss you"--
Well fellows. Pals. I must stop and take up the drudgery again--
My love. To all of you--
Mary Emmett--
Monday.
